# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aburasoba
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aburasoba/a-gei] The ageh was reportedly created in 1965 by Iông-tēⁿ Gím-bûn (楊鄭錦文), who combined various food items sold at her Chin-lí street (真理街) food stall to sell as a new food item.
[src:aburasoba/a-gei] This original ageh consisted of fried tofu that has been emptied of its center, stuffed with cellophane noodles cooked in stewed ground pork, its opening sealed and covered with a carrot and surimi mixture, and then steamed to completion.
[src:aburasoba/a-gei] The dish incorporates several techniques from other dishes, including the stuffing of abura-age in the manner of *inarizushi*, the capping of tofu with surimi to make Yong Tau Foo, and the use of cellophane noodles as a filling for many stuffed pastries.
[src:aburasoba/a-gei] The individual a-gei are served with either a plain soy-based or a sweet chili sauce.
[src:aburasoba/a-gei] A-gei is commonly eaten with a bowl of stuffed fish ball soup in the winter and a glass of cold soy milk in the summer.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] Mazesoba was introduced in the 1950s, with Chinchintei opening up in Musashino City in the 1950s.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] The largest aburasoba chain in the world is Kokoro Mazesoba.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] There are two theories about its origin: one is that Sanko, a restaurant near Hitotsubashi University in Kunitachi City, founded in 1952, started serving it as a snack with alcohol.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] They were likely inspired in the 1950s by soggy ramen noodles.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] The other theory is that Chinchintei, a restaurant near Asia University in the Musashino City district, started selling aburasoba in the 1950s.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] It became popular and ranked in the Shimbun list of Trending Products of the Year.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] In 2002, Myojo Foods launched the "Bubukka" oil-based instant noodles in Kichijoji, Musashino City.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] It is said that it became popular among students because of its relatively low price and large portions.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] According to Great Gidayu, after entering Asia University, a senior student took him to a restaurant that served *aburasoba* as a "rite of passage".
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] Although he didn't think it tasted good at first, he became addicted after going there several times.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] Chinchintei sells noodles, soup, and more by mail order, but most of the orders are from alumni of Asia University.
[src:aburasoba/aburasoba] It has also become a specialty menu item at some student cafeterias.
[src:aburasoba/ants-climbing-a-tree] To make the "ants", meat is marinated for a short time at room temperature while the noodles are soaked to soften.
[src:aburasoba/ants-climbing-a-tree] In a wok, oil is heated until almost smoking.
[src:aburasoba/ants-climbing-a-tree] The scallions, garlic, and ginger are cooked slightly in the wok before the marinated meat is added.
[src:aburasoba/ants-climbing-a-tree] The softened noodles are added to the wok to soak up the flavor and juices.
[src:aburasoba/ants-climbing-a-tree] Dry noodles that have not yet been softened can also be fried in hot oil to add texture to the dish.
[src:aburasoba/ants-climbing-a-tree] The noodles will puff immediately and can be removed with a bamboo or stainless wire skimmer, then set on paper towels to drain before adding to the rest of the dish.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] The **Asia University of Japan** (亜細亜大学, *Ajia Daigaku*) is a private university located in Musashino, Tokyo, Japan that offers courses in Business Administration, Economics, Law, International Relations, Sociology and Sports Science.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] The university was founded in 1941 by Kozo Ota as Koa Senmon Gakko (*Koa Professional School*) on the site of the present Asia University campus.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] Ota believed that education should be based on a spiritual closeness between teachers and students.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] It was a unique school at the time, as it accommodated all students in dormitories divided by course of study; Continental Asia, Southern Pacific Islands and Japan ("Homeland").
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] It shares its name with another university located in Taiwan.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] Asia University has performed consistently well in Division 1 of the Tohto University Baseball League, the intercollegiate baseball league that features 21 prominent universities in the Tokyo area.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] The Asia University (AU) Center for English Language Education (CELE) is a department at Asia University, located in Musashino, Tokyo, Japan.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] Serving the university since 1989, CELE was founded by former AU President Professor Shinkichi Eto.
[src:aburasoba/asia-university-japan] CELE employs between 25 and 30 native English speakers as full-time lecturers.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] The noodles are known as *bakmi* in Indonesia, where they have been adapted to more closely align with the local tastes and into Javanese and Indo cuisine.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] *Bakmi* are between Chinese-style wheat noodles and Japanese udon in thickness, and there are several variants in Indonesia.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] The name *bakmi* literally translates to "meat noodle".
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] In Indonesia, especially in large urban areas such as Jakarta, Medan, and Surabaya, there are many *warung* food stalls, restaurants, and eateries that serve this type of noodle dish, each specialising in different ingredients and toppings.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] Chinese influence is evident in Indonesian food such as *bakmi*, *mie ayam*, *pangsit*, *mie goreng*, and *kwetiau goreng*.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] The words *mie* and *bami*, used in Dutch, come from *bakmi* and were introduced into the Dutch language during the Dutch colonial period in Indonesia.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] Indonesian food is very popular in the Netherlands, and *bami goreng* (fried *bakmi*) is a popular dish.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] In Thailand, wheat-based egg noodles are known as *bami*, which may be ordered as *bami nam* or *bami haeng* (egg noodles with soup and without soup respectively), and the noodles may be used in Chinese style stir-fried dishes.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] In the Philippines, a similar noodle dish is called pancit bam-i or pancit mami, where it is called *bam-i* in Cebuano Bisaya, or *mami/bami* in Tagalog (Filipino).
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] The most common recipe of *bakmi* dish in Indonesia uses chicken meat as the majority of Indonesians are Muslims.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] Chicken noodle (Indonesian: *bakmie ayam or mie ayam*), *mie ayam* is wheat noodle topped with diced chicken meat seasoned in soy sauce.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] *Mie ayam* often accompanied with wonton (Indonesian: *pangsit*) either crispy fried or in soup, and also *bakso* (meatball).
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] *Bakmi ayam* is a popular Chinese Indonesian dish and ubiquitous in Indonesian cities, it can be served in a restaurant to a humble travelling cart.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] The other popular Indonesian *bakmi* recipe is fried *bakmi* (Indonesian: *bakmie goreng* or Indonesian: *mie goreng*).
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] In Indonesia, the most common toppings are diced seasoned chicken with choy sum and fried wonton skin, to a more complete version served with fried or boiled wonton and *bakso* (meatballs).
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] The soup is served in a different bowl, and is added to the noodles by the individual diner according to taste.
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] Several notable Indonesian dishes developed from the original Chinese wheat noodle tradition includes *mie ayam* (chicken noodle) and *mie goreng* (stir fried noodle in sweet soy sauce).
[src:aburasoba/bakmi] *I fu mie* is *bakmi* that is first deep fried and then topped with a thickened gravy of vegetables and meat.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The name *banmian* ('board noodle' or 'block noodle') came from the Hakka method of cutting the noodles into straight strands using a wooden block as ruler.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] In Hakka, some might call it *man-foon-char-guo* (麵粉茶粿) or *dao-ma-chet* (刀嬤切).
[src:aburasoba/banmian] In Hokkien, it was called *mee-hoon-kueh* (麵粉粿; lit.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] 'wheat snack') but what can be found at hawker stalls is generally called *banmian*.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The current style is a mix between the traditional methods of Hakka and Hokkien.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The Hakka initially made the noodle by shaving pieces off a block of dough, commonly made from flour (sometimes egg is added for more flavor), while the Hokkien would roll the dough into a large, flat piece that would then be torn by hand into bite-sized bits.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Traditionally, the dough is hand-kneaded and torn into smaller pieces of dough (about 5 cm or 2 in).
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The dough can also be kneaded using the machine into a variety of shapes, the most common shape being flat strips of noodle.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Banmian is common in China, Malaysia, Singapore and Taiwan.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] It consists of egg noodles served in a flavorful soup, often with meat or fish, vegetables and spices.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Dried anchovies, minced pork, mushrooms, and a leafy vegetable such as sweet potato leaves or sayur manis (*Sauropus androgynus*) are also possible ingredients.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Traditional versions of banmian use egg noodles that are simply a blend of egg, flour, water and salt that is kneaded and then formed into noodles.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] However, modern banmian is frequently made with a pasta maker which cuts noodles in all sizes.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The base of the soup can be water, but is more commonly a type of fish stock.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Normal fish stock can be used, but anchovy stock is a common choice.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Various ingredients such as onions, garlic, ginger and bean paste can be added to the stock to provide more flavor, although some preparations are so simple that nothing more than plain stock is used.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] In Malaysia, dry noodles and soup are served separately.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Dry chilli pan mee is a variant which was invented in Chow Kit, Kuala Lumpur, and is often seen in the Klang Valley.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] This dry noodle is served with minced pork, fried onions, anchovies, and topped with a poached egg which is later stirred into the noodles.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] It is usually served with dry chilli or sambal.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Two common ingredients that are often found across different versions of banmian are mushrooms and anchovies.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The exact type of each might vary, but they are generally added to the stock base.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The mushrooms can be dried and are reconstituted in the broth, while the anchovies may be fried until crispy and then served on top of the soup.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] The anchovies also can be added to the stock for flavor and allowed to break down during cooking.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Once the base stock is completed, nearly anything can be added to complete the banmian.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] This includes vegetables such as green onions, spinach, cabbage and bamboo shoots.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Vinegar is usually added, occasionally with sugar, to balance the flavor.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Restaurants may offer fried minced pork or chunks of white fish as a protein-rich addition.
[src:aburasoba/banmian] Finally, an egg is cracked into the hot broth and allowed to cook until the white is set and the yolk is warmed through.
[src:aburasoba/batchoy] The province of Quezon has a variation of the *batsoy Tagalog*, also known as *bombay* or *bumbay* which derives its name from the similarity of the tied banana leaf pouch to the appearance of the turban worn by Sikhs.
[src:aburasoba/batchoy] The dish consists of finely chopped and seasoned pork offal wrapped in banana leaf and then boiled in water.
[src:aburasoba/batchoy] The dish is served with its cooking broth.
[src:aburasoba/batchoy] The Batchoy Festival is an annual food festival held as part of the larger Dinagyang Festival in Iloilo City.
[src:aburasoba/batchoy] First held in 2020, it features a friendly competition among aficionados and merchants to determine who offers the best-tasting batchoy.
[src:aburasoba/batchoy] The event is a collaboration between SM City Iloilo and the Department of Tourism (DOT), and it is held and celebrated alongside the Grand Iloilo Food Festival at SM City Iloilo Southpoint every January.
[src:aburasoba/beaufort-mee] The noodle traces its origin among the local Chinese in the town of Beaufort in Sabah, usually served in most of the town kopitiams and restaurants.
[src:aburasoba/beaufort-mee] With the increasing popularity throughout Malaysia, other Beaufort mee restaurant branch also has a presence in West Malaysia.
[src:aburasoba/beaufort-mee] The noodle, together with Tenom noodles, is served gravy, where it is prepared by frying the egg noodles until charred.
[src:aburasoba/beaufort-mee] It is often paired with meats such as chicken and sliced pork, either *char siew* (barbecued pork) or *sau nyuk* (roasted pork belly), together with *choy sum* in gravy, and a variation of seafood is also available with slices of shrimp, prawn or fish.
